{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_gibson_ver01/data/sn82016181/00529045670/1924032702/0989.xml":{"full_text":"TODAY\u2019S MARKET IN STOCKS, BONDS, COTTON, GRAINS\nSTOCKS RESIST\nX\nBEAR PRESSURE\nBy Wall Street Journal\nNEW YORK\u2014Stocks today dis\nplayed increasing resistance to pro\nfessional pressure.\nMany sections showed signs of a\nsoldout condition, especially stocks\nlike Steel, Baldwin and American\nCan, which had been depressed by\nbearish drives over the last few\ndays.\nBears\nBut the crowd that had been\npounding away at the market all\nweek were reluctant to the tide turn.\nSo they turned their attention to\nhigh-priced issues like General Elec\ntric and Corn Products, and by\nbreaking these stocks in the late\ntrading created nervousness in the\ngeneral list.\nFollowing a further break in Corn\nProducts, which showed a loss of\nmore than 7 at 171, heavy selling in\nGeneral Electric brought that issue\ndown to 212. off over 18 from the re\nBut these declines had\ncent high.\nno influence on the main body of\nstocks, which held well. Studebaker\nwas well brought above 93.\nImprovement\nStocks gave evidence of a greatly\nimproved technical position in the\nearly dealings, the leading indus\ntrial issues rallying from the start.\nAmerican Can, in which heavy\nselling proceeded all yesterday came\nback sharply to 10512, nearly 2.\nSteel common rebounded to 9914\nagainst yesterday\u2019s low of 98%.\nOther speculative favorites rallied\nin proportion.\nThe overnight news was mixed.\nThe general lists\u2019 improvement was\n'clearly due to internal conditions\ncreated by the overcrowded short in\nterest.\nBaker\nStocks continued to give a better\naccount of themselves thru the first\nhour.\nProfessional attempts to re\nnew the decline thru drives on stocks\nlike Baldwin and Chandler found the\ngeneral list unresponsive.\nGeorge F. Baker, chairman of the\nFirst National Bank of New York,\nis on his way here from Jekyl island.\nBaker has been an optimist and his\nfriends declare he has not changed\nhis views.\nTraders hope for some\nexpression from him on the business\noutlook.\nSilk\nSome disturbance was created in\nthe late morning by an outburst of\nselling in the silk stocks, reflecting\nthe persistent weakness of the raw\nsilk market.\nVan Raalte broke 1\nto 18 and Mallison reached a new\nlow on the move at 181.\nThis\nunsettlement afforded the\nprofessionals an opportunity to at\ntack the industrial leaders.\nBald\nwin was depressed from its early\nhigh of 117%.\nNumerous issues gave indications\nof inside buying.\nOne of these was\nWrigley, which sold at 37 against\nyesterday\u2019s low of 35%.\nThis issue\nexperienced a turnover of 16,900\nshares on the Chicago stock ex\nchange yesterday, while only 2,700\nshares were dealt in here.\nSteady\nIncreasing steadiness marked the\nprincipal stocks in the early after\nBears made no further head\nagainst issues recently under\nnoon,\nway\npressure, so they turned their at\ntention to Corn Products, considered\nnear enough to the year's high to\nmake it vulnerable now that the\nsplit up of its capital has been ap\nproved by the stockholders.\nLIBERTY BONDS\n3\u20182s 1947\n1st 4 \u20184s 1947.\n2d 4Us 1942\n3d 4 \u2018s 1928..\n3d I'cs reg.\n4th 4\u2019is 1938\nHizh\n98.28\n98/26\n99.20 99.17\n99.16\n100.3\n99.14\n99.31 99.31\nLast\n98.28\n99.17\n99.14\n100.1 100.2\n99.31\n99.19 99.16 99.17\nU. S. 4\u2018s 1952.100.10 100.7\n100.7\nU S 1\u2018is \u201952 rg. 100.2\n100.2 100.2\nFOREIGN EXCHANGE\nSterling, demand.\nFrancs.\n1 .ire.\n.0547'\n.0434.\nup\n$4.3014\nup .0007.\n.000212\nup\nBelgian franes. .0432 up .0003)\nFIRE PROOF STORAGE\nKRIEGS EXPRESS\nSTORAGE Co\nMOVING-PACKING SHIPPING\nST N W\noGIG EYE ST. N.W.\nleleplione main 2010~201)\nToday\u2019s New York Stocks\nINDUSTRIALS\nAllied Chem\nAmer Can\nAmer Ice\nAmer T T\nAmer Wool\nCons Gas\nCoca Cola\nFreeport Tex\nGen Asphalt\nInter Paper\nMay Stores\nOwen Bottle\nSears Boe\nHigh\n66\n65%\n1054 103\n8712\n87'2\nClos